Analyzing the critical finetuning data size \(D_{f}^{c}\).While Eq. (1) hinders us from computing \(D_{f}^{c}\) directly, it still allows for theoretical analysis between two finetuning methods when their performance gap is a constant:

\[\hat{\mathcal{L}}_{1}-\hat{\mathcal{L}}_{2}=E_{1}-E_{2}\quad\Longrightarrow\quad \hat{D_{f}^{c}}=H*X^{\gamma},\quad H=\left(\nicefrac{{A_{1}}}{{A_{2}}}\right)^{ \frac{1}{\beta_{1}-\beta_{2}}},\gamma=\frac{\alpha_{2}-\alpha_{1}}{\beta_{1}- \beta_{2}} \tag{3}\]

, which follows another power-law. Intuitively, the exponent \(\gamma\) captures the transferability difference of the two methods to the downstream task as scaling factor \(X\). We summarize the coefficients for

